05694nam a22008535i 9780823289417DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20202020nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232894177 a10.1515/97808232894172doi  a(DE-B1597)571751  a(OCoLC)1198381280  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aSOC0310002bisacsh1 aRodríguez, Dylan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhite Reconstruction :bDomestic Warfare and the Logics of Genocide /cDylan Rodríguez. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b6 b/w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tIntroduction "The Cause Is Effect": Inhabiting White Reconstruction -- t1 "I Used Her Ashes": Multiculturalist White Supremacy/ Counterinsurgency/Domestic War -- t2 "Let the Past Be Forgotten . . .": Remaking White Being, from Reconstruction to Pacification -- t3 Goldwater's Tribal Tattoo: On Origins and Deletions of Post-Raciality -- t4 "Civilization in Its Reddened Waters": Anti- Black, Racial- Colonial Genocide and the Logic of Evisceration -- t5 "Mass Incarceration" as Misnomer: Domestic War and the Narratives of Carceral Reform -- tEpilogue. Abolitionist Imperatives -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWe are in the fray of another signature moment in the long history of the United States as a project of anti-Black and racial-colonial violence. Long before (and well after) November 2016, white nationalism, white terrorism, and white fascist statecraft proliferated state and extra-state terror as a common order. Here, Dylan Rodríguez counter-narrates the long "post-civil rights" half-century as a period of White Reconstruction, in which the struggle to reassemble the ascendancy of White Being toxifies the formal disassembly of U.S. (Jim/Jane Crow) apartheid and permeates the political and institutional logics of diversity, inclusion, formal equality, and "multiculturalist white supremacy." Thinking across a variety of archival, testimonial, visual, and activist texts-from Freedmen's Bureau documents and the "Join LAPD" hiring campaign to Barry Goldwater's hidden tattoo and the Pelican Bay prison strike-White Reconstruction implicates the cultural politics and statecraft of white liberalism and reaction alike, illustrating how anti-Black and racial-colonial domestic war not only survive periods of reform but are the conditions of dominance on which such reforms rely, and through which they often articulate. Throughout White Reconstruction, Rodríguez considers how the creative, imaginative, speculative collective labor of abolitionist praxis responds to legitimated and normalized state violence and terror, showing how the complex and constructive work of abolition can displace and potentially destroy the ascendancy of White Being and Civilization in order to create possibilities for insurgent thriving.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aWhite supremacy movementszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh  aanti-Blackness.  acoloniality.  adecoloniality.  adomestic war.  agenocide.  aincarceration.  amass incarceration.  apolicing.  apost-civil rights.  aracism.  asettler colonialism.  astate violence.  awhite supremacy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eBook package: